            "answer_text": "An answer below cites the old story of milk \"accidentally\" curdling into cheese while stored in a container made from the fourth stomach of a ruminant animal.  Sometimes the story takes place at a domicile and other times while traveling.   I suspect, however, the more likely scenario is that when young ruminants were slaughtered it was noted that the milk in their abomasum wasn't liquid but curdled solids -- this would have predated actual dairy production by who knows how many thousands of years.  By this narrative, humans would have long if underdeveloped experience with the renneting technology of separating the milk solids from the liquids making storage of this valuable food source possible and therefore making the idea of creating and running dairy herds practical from the get-go.   Acid coagulation of the solids from the liquids will occur naturally as milk warms and the indigenous lactic acid bacteria convert lactose in lactic acid, a process that certainly was exploited to make fresh cheeses going way back.  But employing rennet results in a firmer and drier initial curd, allowing ultimately (after salting, pressing, etc, were figured out) for much longer storage without resorting to drying (sun, heat, smoke, etc) like the soft curds of acid cheeses have traditionally undergone to prolong shelf-life beyond fairly immediate consumption.   (One note concerning another answer below:  Rennet is an enzyme that acts on the casein proteins in acidified milk; rennet is not itself an acid.) ",
