            },
            "answer_text": "This is a question, the answer to which is probably lost in the mist of time. It is posited that somewhere in the Middle East, or possibly Central Asia, a herder stored some excess milk in the stomach of a calf and discovered that it had curdled. The curds tasted okay and what was more, they didn't spoil like milk kept in another kind of container. The earliest implement discovered that is indisputably associated with cheese making comes from Poland and dates back to ~5,500 years ago[1]. Using animal parts for storage -- stomachs, bladders, intestines, etc. -- is a prehistoric practice. The stomachs of calves, however, had some sort of \"magic\" ability that did good things to milk. That \"magic\" was later discovered to be rennet. There are cheeses made without animal rennet. Indian paneer, Mexican queso blanco, cottage cheese, French fromage blanc, are all examples of cheese made by curdling milk with acids rather than rennet. There are also \"vegetarian cheeses\" that use plant-derived rennet-like substances. The juice of thistle plants is one such substance. 1.  http://www.livescience.com/25472-first-cheesemakers-discovered.html ",
